[src:viterbi-algorithm/dynamic-programming] Using dynamic programming in the calculation of the *n*th member of the Fibonacci sequence improves its performance greatly.
[src:viterbi-algorithm/dynamic-programming] In particular, `fib(2)` was calculated three times from scratch.
[src:viterbi-algorithm/dynamic-programming] In larger examples, many more values of `fib`, or *subproblems*, are recalculated, leading to an exponential time algorithm.
[src:viterbi-algorithm/dynamic-programming] Now, suppose we have a simple map object, *m*, which maps each value of `fib` that has already been calculated to its result, and we modify our function to use it and update it.
[src:viterbi-algorithm/dynamic-programming] This technique of saving values that have already been calculated is called *memoization*; this is the top-down approach, since we first break the problem into subproblems and then calculate and store values.
[src:viterbi-algorithm/dynamic-programming] In the **bottom-up** approach, we calculate the smaller values of `fib` first, then build larger values from them.
[src:viterbi-algorithm/dynamic-programming] This method also uses O(*n*) time since it contains a loop that repeats n − 1 times, but it only takes constant (O(1)) space, in contrast to the top-down approach which requires O(*n*) space to store the map.
